    "actualResponse": "Most strong AI conferences treat panels as *designed products*, not ‚Äúlet‚Äôs seat smart people and hope.‚Äù Here are the patterns I see working (and that you can borrow for AGI Summit Riyadh), plus what usually fails.\n\n## What the best AI conferences do (and why it works)\n\n### 1) Panels are tightly scoped (one sharp question, not a theme)\nInstead of ‚ÄúThe Future of AI,‚Äù they do:\n- ‚ÄúWhat would change your mind about model scaling?‚Äù\n- ‚ÄúWhat should regulators measure vs. prohibit?‚Äù\n- ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the *one* capability we should fear mismeasuring?‚Äù\n\n**Why:** AI audiences punish vagueness. A narrow question creates disagreement and clarity.\n\n### 2) They program for *productive tension*\nThey intentionally mix:\n- builder vs. safety researcher  \n- open-source vs. closed model incentives  \n- frontier lab vs. enterprise buyer vs. government\n\n**Why:** Without incentive conflict, panels become polite PR.\n\n### 3) Moderators are treated like headliners\nTop conferences pick moderators who:\n- pre-interview each panelist\n- enforce ‚Äúno speeches‚Äù rules\n- interrupt gently but firmly\n- pull specifics (‚Äúgive the metric / timeline / example‚Äù)\n\n**Why:** In AI, the moderator determines whether it‚Äôs insight or marketing.\n\n### 4) They use a repeatable structure (so it doesn‚Äôt drift)\nA common ‚Äúhigh-performing‚Äù format:\n- 60‚Äì90 seconds per panelist: *one non-obvious claim*\n- moderator probes 2 claims into specifics\n- 10 minutes: a structured debate prompt (‚Äúban, pause, license, or nothing?‚Äù)\n- audience Q&A only if curated (app upvoting + moderator filter)\n\n**Why:** Prevents the ‚Äúeveryone gives a mini-keynote‚Äù failure mode.\n\n### 5) They pre-produce the content: prompts, red lines, and receipts\nGood panels often include:\n- a shared pre-read (1 page) so panelists react to the same facts\n- agreed definitions (‚ÄúAGI,‚Äù ‚Äúfrontier,‚Äù ‚Äúalignment,‚Äù ‚Äúsovereignty‚Äù)\n- clear boundaries (what‚Äôs off-limits for security, policy, or corporate reasons)\n\n**Why:** Especially with VIPs/government, you need safety rails without killing substance.\n\n### 6) They design audience Q&A as a product (not a microphone free-for-all)\nCommon approaches:\n- app questions, upvoted + screened\n- ‚Äúlightning Qs‚Äù (30 seconds question, 60 seconds answer)\n- ‚Äúone question per person, no monologues‚Äù rule stated upfront\n\n**Why:** AI crowds include a few people who will hijack Q&A with a manifesto.\n\n### 7) They keep panels shorter than keynotes‚Äîoften 30‚Äì45 minutes\nMany conferences cap panels at 35‚Äì45 minutes unless it‚Äôs a marquee debate.\n\n**Why:** Panels have lower density than a great talk; tighter is better.\n\n## What usually goes wrong (so you can avoid it)\n- Panelists aren‚Äôt briefed ‚Üí everyone speaks in slogans.\n- Moderator is too deferential ‚Üí no follow-ups, no friction.\n- Too many people (6‚Äì8) ‚Üí no one says anything memorable.\n- Audience Q&A dominates ‚Üí lowest-signal section eats the clock.\n\n## One decision to make it concrete for AGI Summit Riyadh\nDo you want your main-stage panels to feel more like **‚Äúpolicy-grade clarity‚Äù** (structured, ministerial-safe, consensus-forward) or **‚Äúfrontier debate‚Äù** (more tension, more specificity, higher heat)?\n\nReply with one: **policy-grade clarity** or **frontier debate**, and I‚Äôll suggest a panel structure + moderator brief that fits.",
